Article 58:  The President of the Republic shall be prosecuted and judged in common crimes by the Supreme Court, and of crimes of impeachment by a Special Tribunal, which will have as President of that court and shall consist of nine judges, and three Ministers of the Supreme Court, three members of the Federal Senate, and three members of the Chamber of Deputies. The President will have only a casting vote.    1: The Special Court's judges will be chosen by raffle (lot) within eleven business days after the accusation was decreed under section 4, or pursuant to section 5 of this article.   2 The complaint will be offered to the President of the Supreme Court, which will immediately summon the Special Committee of Investigation, consisting of a Minister of the said Court, a member of the Senate and a representative of the Chamber of Deputies, elected by the respective corporations annually .  3 The investigation committee will continue, at its discretion, the investigation of the defendants facts, consulting with the President, and will send a report of the respective documents to the Chamber of Deputies   4  With the documents and report submitted by the Special Committee of investigation, the Chamber of Deputies will within 30 days of the accusation decide to continue or not the accusation. If affirmed, it will send all the pieces of the investigation to the President of the Special Tribunal in order to be tired  5. Not in answer to the Chamber of Deputies on the accusation the date specified in 4, the President of the Special Committee of Investigation will send copies of the report and documents to the President of the Supreme Court so that he can start the formation of the Special Court, and this court will decide if the accusation will continue, and, in the case where it is affirmative, it will prosecute and judge the complaint.  6 Given the accusation, the President of the Republic will be, as of then, removed from his office   7. The Special Court will be able apply only the penalty of removal from office, with denying until the five-year maximum the exercise of any public functions, without prejudice to the civil and criminal actions appropriate in kind.

event_notes: I scanned through the document searching different key words, but I'm surprised it didn't describe both the House and Senate's responsibilities for selecting Magistrates. The appointment process appears very similar to Colombia's 1910 proceedings, but responsibilities are not separated here like they were in 1910. Instead, Article 149 states that the Legislative Houses select Supreme Court Magistrates.
translated_text: Article 149: The Magistrates of the Supreme Court of Justice will be selected by the Legislative Houses, from short lists of three candidates that the President of the Republic will pass to them.

event_notes: I'm highly confident in my translation of the document and I don't think I'm missing any information. However, the process becomes somewhat cloudy when described in Article 97 (2-3). Declaration 2 describes how the Senate can remove an individual, not specifically a Supreme Court Justice, for crimes committed in the exercise of his/her functions and for mis-conduct. That information is included in the flowchart. It then moves on in Declaration 3 to say that individuals committing criminal acts or common crimes will be brought in front of the Supreme Court. I did not include that information in the flow chart because I don't see how the Supreme Court can try its own members, but I still wanted to mention this.     Lastly, Article 97, Declaration 4 describes how the Senate can create a delegation within its own body to make a judgment and final decision. That seems separate than the Senate deciding itself, so I made this process separate on the flow chart.
translated_text: Article 97 (2): If the accusation refers to crimes committed in the exercise of their functions or to indignity for misconduct, the Senate cannot impose another penalty than dismissal from employment, or the temporary deprivation or absolute loss of political rights...    Article 97 (4): The Senate can submit the instruction of the processes to a delegation of its body, that will decide the judgment and definitive sentence, which will be pronounced in public session, by at least two-thirds of the Senators that come together.    Article 102 (5): The House of Representatives has the power to accuse, before the Senate, when there are just causes, Magistrates of the Supreme Court of Justice.    Article 148: The period of the Magistrates of the Supreme Court of Justice will be five years, and they can be reelected indefinitely.

translated_text: Article 34 (30), page 11: Congress has the power to examine and pass judgment on, according to law, on the accusations that legislators propose, particular individuals or bodies, against...Ministers of the Supreme Court.    The accusations can be proposed during the period of office of the respective employees or up until one year after.    For infractions committed in the exercise of official functions, Congress cannot impose another penalty than the suspension or loss of office and to declare the defendant, temporarily or perpetually, unfit to perform public office. If the material fact of the accusation made him liable for infringement that merits another penalty, one will continue trial before the judge or respective court.    If the accusation does not refer to official conduct, Congress is limited to declare whether or not there will be judgment and, in the affirmative case, will place the accused to the disposal of the respective Judge or Court.    If Congress discards the accusation, it cannot renew it by the same motives. Georgia's Constitutional Court shall be comprised of 9 judges-- members of the Constitutional Court. 3 members of the Court shall be appointed by Georgia's President, 3 members are elected by more than 1/2 of Parliament, 3 members are appointed by the Supreme Court. Judges of the Constitutional Court may serve for a term of 10 years. The Constitutional Court itself shall choose its Chairman for a period of 5 years.  3. Judes of the Constitutional Court may not have held this position before.   4. Members of Georgia's Constitutional Court may be citizens of at least 30 years of age, if the member has higher legal education. Selection, appointment, and removal of Constitutional Court members, as well as other proceedings of the Constitutional Court shall be determined by rule of law.

translated_text: Article 205 (9): Congress has the power to elect for the period that corresponds with the nomination of candidates that the Nominating Board proposes, the Magistrates of the Supreme Court of Justice.    Article 308: The Supreme Court of Justice is integrated with 15 Magistrates.    Article 311: The Magistrates of the Supreme Court of Justice will be elected by the National Congress, with the favorable vote of 2/3 parts of all members, from a nomination of candidates no less than 3 for each one of the Magistrates to be elected.    When presented with the proposal of the total number of Magistrate candidates, an election will follow.    In case of not achieving the majority qualified for the election of the complete nomination of Magistrates, it shall move to a direct and secret vote to elect individually the Magistrates that are missing, as many times as necessary, until achieving the favorable vote of 2/3 parts. The procedures for the political trial are unclear.      Nancy Reconciliation note summer 2016: Constitution states that justices of the supreme court are subject to removal, but the process is uncelar:    'Article 234  [Inserted by Decree No. 231-2012 as ratified by Decree No. 8-2013]  Political Trial [Juicio Politico/Impeachment] against the President of the Republic and [persons] Designated Presidential, Magistrates of the Supreme Court of Justice, Deputies of the National Congress and Central American Parliament, Municipal Corporations, and any public servant elected by the National Congress[,] proceeds when grave denunciation in the performance of their office [cargo] exist against them, for realizing actions [actuaciónes] contrary to the Constitution of the Republic or the national interest and for manifest negligence, incapacity or incompetence to perform the office. Without prejudice to administrative, civil and penal responsibility, the dismissal from the office will be the only consequence derived from the responsibility decreed through a political trial.  When the denunciation is against the President of the Republic, the processing [tramitación] of the process of prosecution and his dismissal must be approved by the three-quarters parts of the total of the Deputies, in the other cases it will be by two-thirds of the Chamber.  The President of the Republic may only be dismissed from his office by the National Congress through Political Trial.  The implementation of Political Trial and its effects are not subject to jurisdictional control and the Decree emitted to that effect does not require [the] sanction of the Executive Power.  Political Trial consist of two (2) stages, the investigative Stage that will last [the time] established in the Special Law which to that effect will be emitted and the Stage of discussion and vote, that will last up to five (5) days, counted from the presentation of the report [informe] to the Plenary on the part of the Special Commission.'

Section II, Article 234 discusses political trials, in particular, which public servants can be tried for what types of behavior.     Article 205 states, however, that the National Congress has the power 'To conduct [realizar] the Political Trial [Juicio Poltico] in accordance with the procedure established in the Special Law for Political Trial...'

translated_text: Article 89 (18): The Executive has the power to appoint Ministers of the Supreme Court of Justice and submit the appointments, the licenses, and the resignations of them, to the approval of the House of Senators or the Permanent Commission, in this case.    Article 94: ...The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation will be composed of 16 Ministers    Article 96: The nominations of Ministers of the the Supreme Court of Justice will be made by the President of the Republic and subjected to the approval of the House of Senators, which will award or deny this endorsement, within the non-extendable period of ten days. If the Senate fails to decided within this term, the appointment shall be deemed approved. Without the approval of the Senate, the appointed Ministers of the Supreme Court cannot take the vacant seats. In the case of the House of Senators not approving two successive appointments in respect to the same vacancy, the President will make a third appointment that will take effect from then on, as provisional, and that will be subject to the approval of the Senate, in the following ordinary period of sessions. In this period of sessions, within the first ten days, the Senate must approve or reject the appointment, and if it approves or fails to deny, the named provisional Minister will continue in their functions with a definitive character. If the Senate rejects the appointment, the provisional Minister will cease their functions from then on, and the President of the Republic will submit a new appointment to the approval of the Senate, in the mentioned terms

This amendment contains Ten Additional Articles to the Constitution of ROC. These articles replaced the 10 articles adopted in the April 1991 amendment and the 8 articles adopted in the May 1992 amendment. These were then replaced by the 11 Additional Articles adopted in July 1997, and later by the Eleven Additional Articles adopted in April 2000.    Article 4 of this amendment states that Article 79 of the Constitution 'shall not apply'  to the appointment process. It seems to replace confirmation of the judges by the Control Yuan with consent by the National Assembly instead.

This amendment contains Ten Additional Articles to the Constitution of ROC. These articles replaced the 10 articles adopted in the April 1991 amendment and the 8 articles adopted in the May 1992 amendment. These were then replaced by the 11 Additional Articles adopted in July 1997, and later by the Eleven Additional Articles adopted in April 2000.    The amendment states that impeachment process should be initiated by 2 members of Control Yuan. This process was coded with the original ROC Constitution information. Once again, it should be noted that removal process ends with 'impeachment initiated'

This amendment contains 11 Additional Articles adopted in July 1997, which replaces the Ten Additional Articles to the Constitution of ROC of 1994. The 1997 amendment was later replaced by the Eleven Additional Articles adopted in April 2000.    Article 5 was set to take effect in 2003 and states that 'the pertinent provisions of Article 79 of the Constitution shall not apply' to the appointment process. Judges appointed in 2004 are to serve a 4 year term, instead of 8 years

This amendment contains Ten Additional Articles to the Constitution of ROC. These articles replaced the 10 articles adopted in the April 1991 amendment and the 8 articles adopted in the May 1992 amendment. These were then replaced by the 11 Additional Articles adopted in July 1997, and later by the Eleven Additional Articles adopted in April 2000.    Article 7 of the Additional Articles mentions impeachment briefly- stating it should be initiated by 2 Control Yuan members. Much of the process remains the same as original Constitution of ROC in 1947. Should be noted that removal process ends when impeachment is initiated, but the information is not provided for this.

They must Venezuelan by birth and over thirty years old. The two candidates for the Court of Appeals must be lawyers of the Republic; and the Federal Court, one must have this status at least.      102.  To make the election, States will be divided into ten groups: Miranda and Aragua, Carabobo and Guarico. Sucre and Nueva Esparta, Barcelona and Maturin, Bolivar and Apure, Portuguesa and Zamora, Cojedes and Yaracuy, Lara and Falcon, Trujillo and Zulia and Mrida and Tchira; and it must be ensured that each group is represented in both courts( Federal court and court of appeals); and that each state that forms these groups must also have their own representation in one or the other court, and they will do this by choosing among their candidates, a principal candidates and one alternate to the Court that they are representing.    Paragraph 1: If the Senate finds that one or some of the candidates do no fulfill all the requirements of the law, it will chose replacements temporarily. In each case the Legislative Assembly and the Municipal Council of the Federal District will participate respectively, in order to perfect the election. These aforementioned bodies will participate with the Senate in improving the selection and they will make the new election.
